body:
@mpbrigham Can you run the command below and see what it prints out?

```
mlflow run https://github.com/harupy/mlflow-example.git -P alpha=5.0
```

The output should look like:

```
xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx
artifact uri: file:///Users/yyy/xxx/mlflow/mlruns/0/b3ce4342eda643cba1ca752cd7671300/artifacts
```

@harupy sure thing, here it is:

```
xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx
artifact uri: ./mlruns/0/303cd1563bfd495eba06523d9021b12c/artifacts
2020/08/26 10:21:48 INFO mlflow.projects: === Run (ID '303cd1563bfd495eba06523d9021b12c') succeeded ===
```

@mpbrigham Can you run this code and see if it logs a trained model?

```python
import os

from sklearn.linear_model import ElasticNet

import mlflow
import mlflow.sklearn


if __name__ == "__main__":
    with mlflow.start_run():
        lr = ElasticNet()
        mlflow.sklearn.log_model(lr, "model")
```
@harupy Yes, the above code successfully saves a trained model.
Do you use powershell or command prompt?
Can you run `mlflow run https://github.com/harupy/mlflow-example.git -P alpha=5.0` in powershell?

I get the same results as with the command prompt:
- trained model not saved with `https://github.com/harupy/mlflow-example.git -P alpha=5.0`
- trained model saved with the python code above
